233, 234. 1 discard the arrangement in the MSS. and make two short lines instead of one long, the first a Catalectie Iambic Dimeter, the second a Oretic Trimeter. The second might be scanned as an Iambic Dimeter acatalectic, though it is more likely that the change in sense (Sed id διο.) should coincide With the change in metre. Some substitute for sese the form sesed and retain the single line of the MSS„ an Iambie Octonarius. Sesed occurs on an old inscription (QLL. xi. 3078), but is hardly Plautine.

236. Hermann's change of Sunt to Fama is generally accepted, though confusion of S and F is as uncommon as that of minuscule s and f is common. It is conceivable that Plautus might use sunt ea· as well asflo ex (cf. Alere. 129 exc hoc metu ut sim certus, Epid. 644 di me ea· perdita seruatam cupiunt). The first foot would then have to be sant nunc, and the linc Bacchiae catalectic or possibly ‘contracted' Cretic (cf. v. 217). I follow Seyffert in making Philocrates’ speech begin at Nunc rather than at Quod (v. 237> or Pol (v. 238). Tyndarus has already told Philocrates what he wishes from him.
